{"key":"processedPost-11111438","value":{"id":11111438,"first":11109955,"last":11111449,"when":1253717835,"utime":"09/23/09 05:57 PM","content":"<blockquote>Quote:<br />when i birth my cakes, i simply open the jar, dump off the dry verm layer, pop the cakes into my hand, rinse my jar, fill it with water, pop the cake back in, and top off the jar before putting the lid back on.<br /></blockquote><br /><br />That's not a very effective method.&nbsp; The mycelium cells hydrate by having a higher pressure outside the cell than inside(osmosis).&nbsp; Therefore, you'll get better hydration if they're in a larger container, being held down by something heavy on top.&nbsp; This way, the water pressure is enough to force water through the cell walls.&nbsp; Remember, you're not hydrating the substrate, but instead you're hydrating each individual cell of mycelium.&nbsp; That's why it takes roughly 24 hours.<br /><br />Follow the link in my sig and watch all four brf tek videos.&nbsp; You'll see a video demonstration of the method I recommend for soaking cakes.<br />RR","title":"Re: Dunking","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}